<font color="#FF0000">RESPONSE TO KEN</font><br>
<tt>Thu May  1 23:07:00 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Ken,<br>
    My father-in-law was a WWII &amp; Korean Vet.  He lost an arm in Korea when his truck was sideswiped.  Was a mess sergeant and a good one.<br>
    I must take exception to the phrase &quot;fawn all attentions on Vietnam Vets&quot;.  Could have fooled me.  It's taken 25-30 years of pulling teeth to get the bare minimum attention from the VA on Agent Orange exposure problems.  Some of the problems of WWII and Korean Vets like phlebitis due to frostbite in Korea and Europe are getting recognized now, in part, because Vietnam Vets are continually putting the goveernment's feet to the fire.  Not all the attention Vietnam Vets get is welcome either.  The first thing I have to do, when I go into a high school to give a class on the war, is dispel the notion (thanks to Hollywood) that all Vietnam Vets are either crazed druggies or Rambo.  If a WWII  or Korean Vet commits a serious crime, no one mentions he is a vet, but if he served in Vietnam, the words &quot;Vietnam Veteran&quot; are always in the first or second sentence.<br><br>
    Suggest you visit the Korean War Memorial in DC.  The wall portion doesn't have names, but has ghostly images in the stone peering out at the bone tired infantry squad that looks like it's on its way back fron going through the ringer.  I found it very moving and impressive.<br><br>
    We may have a Korean War Memorial here in Philly some day; if two groups of Korean Veterans can bury the hatchet and work together.  The ground is set aside, and the short street on one side was renamed 38th Parallel Place.
<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney, &quot;professor&quot;, 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


